{"title_page": "Rob Flello", "text_new": "{{short description|British Liberal Democrat politician|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{BLP sources|date=March 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2014}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix =\n| name = Rob Flello\n| honorific-suffix = \n| image = \n| office = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] <br /> for [[Stoke-on-Trent South (UK Parliament constituency)|Stoke-on-Trent South]]\n| parliament =\n| predecessor = [[George Stevenson (MP)|George Stevenson]]\n| successor = [[Jack Brereton]]\n| term_start = 5 May 2005\n| term_end = 5 May 2017 \n| birth_name = Robert Charles Douglas Flello \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1966|1|14|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Birmingham]], England\n| nationality = [[United Kingdom|British]]\n| spouse =\n| party = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] until September 2019\n[[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]]\n| alma_mater = [[University of Wales, Bangor]]\n| occupation =\n| profession =\n| majority =\n|}}\n\n'''Robert Charles Douglas Flello''' (born 14 January 1966) is a British [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrat]] politician who was [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]  [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Stoke-on-Trent South (UK Parliament constituency)|Stoke-on-Trent South]] from 2005 to 2017.  He lost his seat at the [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017 general election]] to [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] candidate [[Jack Brereton]].\n\n==Early life==\nFlello was born in [[Bournville]], [[Birmingham]]. He attended [[Bournville Junior School|Bournville Junior]] and Infant schools before going to [[King's Norton Boys' School]]. At age 18 he went to [[University of Wales, Bangor]] to read Chemistry. He graduated in 1987 with a B.Sc (Hons).\n\n==Career==\nAfter graduating, Flello worked for a short time at [[Cadbury]] in [[Bournville]] before joining the [[Inland Revenue]]. In 1989 he left to join [[Price Waterhouse]] accountants as a personal tax advisor. In 1995 he moved to [[Arthur Andersen]]. In 1999, he co-founded Platts Flello Limited, tax and financial advisors. In late 2003 he left to work as the CEO of Malachi Community Trust until December 2004.\n\n==Political career==\nFlello was elected as a councillor to the [[Longbridge]] ward of [[Birmingham City Council]] in 2002, stepping down in 2004. He is a former chairman of the [[Birmingham Northfield (UK Parliament constituency)|Birmingham Northfield]] [[Constituency Labour Party]]. He served as a governor at the [[Newman University, Birmingham|Newman College]] in [[Bartley Green]], and was Chair of Governors for both Colmers Farm infants and junior schools. He was also a governor at The Meadows primary school. He served as a regional organiser for the Labour Party in 2004 until his election to [[Palace of Westminster|Westminster]].{{citation needed|date=May 2015}}\n\n===Parliament===\nFlello was elected to the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] at the [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005 general election]] for [[Stoke-on-Trent South (UK Parliament constituency)|Stoke-on-Trent South]] following the retirement of [[George Stevenson (MP)|George Stevenson]]. Flello held the seat with a majority of 8,681 and made his [[maiden speech]] on 19 May 2005.<ref>[https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200506/cmhansrd/cm050519/debtext/50519-20.htm#50519-20_spnew0 House of Commons Hansard Debates for 19 May 2005 (pt 20)]. Publications.parliament.uk (19 May 2005); retrieved 9 May 2015.</ref>\n\nIn parliament he was a member of the [[Science and Technology Select Committee]]. While Labour were in government he served as [[Parliamentary Private Secretary]] first to the [[Lord Chancellor]], [[Charles Falconer, Baron Falconer of Thoroton]], then to the [[Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government]], [[Hazel Blears]], and finally after 2009 to the [[Secretary of State for Defence]], [[Bob Ainsworth]].{{citation needed|date=May 2015}}\n\nIn June 2016, Labour Party activists in Stoke-on-Trent South proposed a motion of no confidence in Flello after he called on Labour leader [[Jeremy Corbyn]] to \"do the decent thing and resign\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stokesentinel.co.uk/labour-activists-propose-motion-of-no-confidence-in-rob-flello-mp-as-he-called-on-corbyn-to-resign/story-29454491-detail/story.html|title=Labour activists propose motion of no confidence in Rob Flello MP as he called on Corbyn to resign|date=29 June 2016|website=Stoke Sentinel}}{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> He had supported [[Owen Smith]] in the failed attempt to replace [[Jeremy Corbyn]] in the [[2016 Labour Party (UK) leadership election|2016 Labour leadership election]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://labourlist.org/2016/07/which-mps-and-meps-have-nominated-owen-smith/|title=Full list of MPs and MEPs backing challenger Owen Smith|date=2016-07-21|website=LabourList|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-07-15}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019 he defected to the Lib Dems and was selected as their parliamentary candidate for his old seat.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stokesentinel.co.uk/news/stoke-on-trent-news/look-whos-back-former-potteries-3524124|title=Former Stoke-on-Trent Labour MP Rob Flello to fight old seat \u2013 as a Lib Dem|last=Corrigan|first=Phil|date=12 November 2019|website=Stoke Sentinel}}</ref> 36 hours after his selection, however, the Lib Dems deselected Flello, citing \"how greatly his values diverge from ours\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stokesentinel.co.uk/news/stoke-on-trent-news/cut-short-former-stoke-trent-3531744|title=Cut short! Lib Dems deselect former Labour MP Rob Flello after just 36 hours|first=Joe|last=Burn|date=12 November 2019|website=Stoke Sentinel}}</ref> It is believed that they objected to his socially conservative views on abortion and same-sex marriage.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-stoke-staffordshire-50401318|title=Former Labour MP deselected as Lib Dem candidate|date=13 November 2019|publisher=[[BBC News]]|accessdate=5 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Social views===\nFlello is a convert to Catholicism and stated in 2014 \"I could no more leave my faith at the door of the House of Commons than I could my name or my gender or my arms and legs\". He was a member of the anti-abortion All-Party Parliamentary Pro-Life Group.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.catholicherald.co.uk/commentandblogs/2017/06/09/this-was-a-grim-night-for-christians-and-pro-lifers-in-parliament/|title=This was a grim night for Christians and pro-lifers in parliament - CatholicHerald.co.uk|date=9 June 2017|publisher=}}</ref> Flello also opposes [[Same-sex marriage in the United Kingdom|same-sex marriage]] and was one of the few Labour MPs to vote against the [[Marriage (Same Sex Couples) Act 2013]], citing his religious views.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pinknews.co.uk/2013/01/20/labour-shadow-justice-minister-rob-flello-to-vote-against-same-sex-marriage-equality/|title=Labour Shadow Justice Minister Rob Flello to vote against same-sex marriage equality|publisher=[[PinkNews]]}}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\nIn 2007 Flello was accused of [[filibuster]]ing a fellow Labour backbencher's [[Private Members' Bills in the Parliament of the United Kingdom|private members bill]]. The bill, introduced by neighbouring Staffordshire MP [[Paul Farrelly]], aimed to give temporary and agency workers similar employment rights to permanent staff. It was backed by the [[Unite the Union|Unite]] trade union. The incident provoked an angry response in the ''[[Daily Mirror]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/top-stories/2007/03/07/shame-of-mouthy-mp-115875-18716285|title=SHAME OF MOUTHY MP|date=7 March 2007|work=mirror.co.uk|accessdate=13 January 2013}}{{better source|date=March 2017|reason=Tabloids are not acceptable sources for [[WP:BLP]]s}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Flello blamed \"shocking congestion\" in London on the loss of tarmac from building cycle lanes, which received a critical response from bike charity the [[London Cycling Campaign]]<ref>{{cite news|last1=Batchelor|first1=Tom|title=MP says cycle lanes should be scrapped to make more room for cars|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/labour-mp-rob-flello-comment-blame-cycle-lanes-for-city-traffic-transport-select-committee-a7519561.html|work=The Independent|date=10 January 2017}}</ref> and cycling website road.cc,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bowden|first1=Alex|title=Senior MP asks whether 'loss of tarmac' for cycle lanes is causing London's congestion problems as Government launches urban congestion inquiry|url=http://road.cc/content/news/215325-senior-mp-asks-whether-loss-tarmac-cycle-lanes-causing-londons-congestion|work=road.cc|date=10 January 2017}}</ref> both pointing out that tarmac had been repurposed to another form of transport and that the increased number of journeys overall in Central London were what was causing congestion, not the segregated cycle tracks that are on less than 1%<ref>{{cite web|last1=RH|first1=Andrew|title=24 London Boroughs installed ZERO segregated cycle-lanes since the last London elections.|url=http://stopkillingcyclists.org/2014/04/02/press-release-wall-of-death-24-london-boroughs-installed-zero-segregated-cycle-lanes-since-the-last-london-elections/|website=SKC|date=2 April 2014}}</ref> of London roads.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official website|http://www.robertflello.com}}\n*{{UK MP links|parliament=rob-flello/1569|publicwhip=rob_flello|theywork=rob_flello}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[George Stevenson (MP)|George Stevenson]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Stoke-on-Trent South (UK Parliament constituency)|Stoke-on-Trent South]]|years=[[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005]]\u2013[[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Jack Brereton]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Labour Party shadow cabinet election, 2010}}\n{{West Midlands Labour Party MPs}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Flello, Robert}}\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Bangor University]]\n[[Category:British Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Councillors in Birmingham, West Midlands]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:People from Birmingham, West Midlands]]\n[[Category:British anti-abortion activists]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2005\u20132010]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2010\u20132015]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2015\u20132017]]\n[[Category:Liberal Democrats (UK) parliamentary candidates]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British Liberal Democrat politician|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{BLP sources|date=March 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2014}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix =\n| name = Rob Flello\n| honorific-suffix = \n| image = \n| office = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] <br /> for [[Stoke-on-Trent South (UK Parliament constituency)|Stoke-on-Trent South]]\n| parliament =\n| predecessor = [[George Stevenson (MP)|George Stevenson]]\n| successor = [[Jack Brereton]]\n| term_start = 5 May 2005\n| term_end = 5 May 2017 \n| birth_name = Robert Charles Douglas Flello \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1966|1|14|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Birmingham]], England\n| nationality = [[United Kingdom|British]]\n| spouse =\n| party = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] until September 2019\n[[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]]\n| alma_mater = [[University of Wales, Bangor]]\n| occupation =\n| profession =\n| majority =\n|}}\n\n'''Robert Charles Douglas Flello''' (born 14 January 1966) is a British [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrat]] politician who was [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]  [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Stoke-on-Trent South (UK Parliament constituency)|Stoke-on-Trent South]] from 2005 to 2017.  He lost his seat at the [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017 general election]] to [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] candidate [[Jack Brereton]].\n\n==Early life==\nFlello was born in [[Bournville]], [[Birmingham]]. He attended [[Bournville Junior School|Bournville Junior]] and Infant schools before going to [[King's Norton Boys' School]]. At age 18 he went to [[University of Wales, Bangor]] to read Chemistry. He graduated in 1987 with a B.Sc (Hons).\n\n==Career==\nAfter graduating, Flello worked for a short time at [[Cadbury]] in [[Bournville]] before joining the [[Inland Revenue]]. In 1989 he left to join [[Price Waterhouse]] accountants as a personal tax advisor. In 1995 he moved to [[Arthur Andersen]]. In 1999, he co-founded Platts Flello Limited, tax and financial advisors. In late 2003 he left to work as the CEO of Malachi Community Trust until December 2004.\n\n==Political career==\nFlello was elected as a councillor to the [[Longbridge]] ward of [[Birmingham City Council]] in 2002, stepping down in 2004. He is a former chairman of the [[Birmingham Northfield (UK Parliament constituency)|Birmingham Northfield]] [[Constituency Labour Party]]. He served as a governor at the [[Newman University, Birmingham|Newman College]] in [[Bartley Green]], and was Chair of Governors for both Colmers Farm infants and junior schools. He was also a governor at The Meadows primary school. He served as a regional organiser for the Labour Party in 2004 until his election to [[Palace of Westminster|Westminster]].{{citation needed|date=May 2015}}\n\n===Parliament===\nFlello was elected to the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] at the [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005 general election]] for [[Stoke-on-Trent South (UK Parliament constituency)|Stoke-on-Trent South]] following the retirement of [[George Stevenson (MP)|George Stevenson]]. Flello held the seat with a majority of 8,681 and made his [[maiden speech]] on 19 May 2005.<ref>[https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200506/cmhansrd/cm050519/debtext/50519-20.htm#50519-20_spnew0 House of Commons Hansard Debates for 19 May 2005 (pt 20)]. Publications.parliament.uk (19 May 2005); retrieved 9 May 2015.</ref>\n\nIn parliament he was a member of the [[Science and Technology Select Committee]]. While Labour were in government he served as [[Parliamentary Private Secretary]] first to the [[Lord Chancellor]], [[Charles Falconer, Baron Falconer of Thoroton]], then to the [[Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government]], [[Hazel Blears]], and finally after 2009 to the [[Secretary of State for Defence]], [[Bob Ainsworth]].{{citation needed|date=May 2015}}\n\nIn June 2016, Labour Party activists in Stoke-on-Trent South proposed a motion of no confidence in Flello after he called on Labour leader [[Jeremy Corbyn]] to \"do the decent thing and resign\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stokesentinel.co.uk/labour-activists-propose-motion-of-no-confidence-in-rob-flello-mp-as-he-called-on-corbyn-to-resign/story-29454491-detail/story.html|title=Labour activists propose motion of no confidence in Rob Flello MP as he called on Corbyn to resign|date=29 June 2016|website=Stoke Sentinel}}{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> He had supported [[Owen Smith]] in the failed attempt to replace [[Jeremy Corbyn]] in the [[2016 Labour Party (UK) leadership election]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://labourlist.org/2016/07/which-mps-and-meps-have-nominated-owen-smith/|title=Full list of MPs and MEPs backing challenger Owen Smith|date=2016-07-21|website=LabourList|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-07-15}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019 he defected to the Lib Dems and was selected as their parliamentary candidate for his old seat.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stokesentinel.co.uk/news/stoke-on-trent-news/look-whos-back-former-potteries-3524124|title=Former Stoke-on-Trent Labour MP Rob Flello to fight old seat \u2013 as a Lib Dem|last=Corrigan|first=Phil|date=12 November 2019|website=Stoke Sentinel}}</ref> 36 hours after his selection, however, the Lib Dems deselected Flello, citing \"how greatly his values diverge from ours\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stokesentinel.co.uk/news/stoke-on-trent-news/cut-short-former-stoke-trent-3531744|title=Cut short! Lib Dems deselect former Labour MP Rob Flello after just 36 hours|first=Joe|last=Burn|date=12 November 2019|website=Stoke Sentinel}}</ref> It is believed that they objected to his socially conservative views on abortion and same-sex marriage.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-stoke-staffordshire-50401318|title=Former Labour MP deselected as Lib Dem candidate|date=13 November 2019|publisher=[[BBC News]]|accessdate=5 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Social views===\nFlello is a convert to Catholicism and stated in 2014 \"I could no more leave my faith at the door of the House of Commons than I could my name or my gender or my arms and legs\". He was a member of the anti-abortion All-Party Parliamentary Pro-Life Group.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.catholicherald.co.uk/commentandblogs/2017/06/09/this-was-a-grim-night-for-christians-and-pro-lifers-in-parliament/|title=This was a grim night for Christians and pro-lifers in parliament - CatholicHerald.co.uk|date=9 June 2017|publisher=}}</ref> Flello also opposes [[Same-sex marriage in the United Kingdom|same-sex marriage]] and was one of the few Labour MPs to vote against the [[Marriage (Same Sex Couples) Act 2013]], citing his religious views.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pinknews.co.uk/2013/01/20/labour-shadow-justice-minister-rob-flello-to-vote-against-same-sex-marriage-equality/|title=Labour Shadow Justice Minister Rob Flello to vote against same-sex marriage equality|publisher=[[PinkNews]]}}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\nIn 2007 Flello was accused of [[filibuster]]ing a fellow Labour backbencher's [[Private Members' Bills in the Parliament of the United Kingdom|private members bill]]. The bill, introduced by neighbouring Staffordshire MP [[Paul Farrelly]], aimed to give temporary and agency workers similar employment rights to permanent staff. It was backed by the [[Unite the Union|Unite]] trade union. The incident provoked an angry response in the ''[[Daily Mirror]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/top-stories/2007/03/07/shame-of-mouthy-mp-115875-18716285|title=SHAME OF MOUTHY MP|date=7 March 2007|work=mirror.co.uk|accessdate=13 January 2013}}{{better source|date=March 2017|reason=Tabloids are not acceptable sources for [[WP:BLP]]s}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Flello blamed \"shocking congestion\" in London on the loss of tarmac from building cycle lanes, which received a critical response from bike charity the [[London Cycling Campaign]]<ref>{{cite news|last1=Batchelor|first1=Tom|title=MP says cycle lanes should be scrapped to make more room for cars|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/labour-mp-rob-flello-comment-blame-cycle-lanes-for-city-traffic-transport-select-committee-a7519561.html|work=The Independent|date=10 January 2017}}</ref> and cycling website road.cc,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bowden|first1=Alex|title=Senior MP asks whether 'loss of tarmac' for cycle lanes is causing London's congestion problems as Government launches urban congestion inquiry|url=http://road.cc/content/news/215325-senior-mp-asks-whether-loss-tarmac-cycle-lanes-causing-londons-congestion|work=road.cc|date=10 January 2017}}</ref> both pointing out that tarmac had been repurposed to another form of transport and that the increased number of journeys overall in Central London were what was causing congestion, not the segregated cycle tracks that are on less than 1%<ref>{{cite web|last1=RH|first1=Andrew|title=24 London Boroughs installed ZERO segregated cycle-lanes since the last London elections.|url=http://stopkillingcyclists.org/2014/04/02/press-release-wall-of-death-24-london-boroughs-installed-zero-segregated-cycle-lanes-since-the-last-london-elections/|website=SKC|date=2 April 2014}}</ref> of London roads.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official website|http://www.robertflello.com}}\n*{{UK MP links|parliament=rob-flello/1569|publicwhip=rob_flello|theywork=rob_flello}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[George Stevenson (MP)|George Stevenson]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Stoke-on-Trent South (UK Parliament constituency)|Stoke-on-Trent South]]|years=[[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005]]\u2013[[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Jack Brereton]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Labour Party shadow cabinet election, 2010}}\n{{West Midlands Labour Party MPs}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Flello, Robert}}\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Bangor University]]\n[[Category:British Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Councillors in Birmingham, West Midlands]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:People from Birmingham, West Midlands]]\n[[Category:British anti-abortion activists]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2005\u20132010]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2010\u20132015]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2015\u20132017]]\n[[Category:Liberal Democrats (UK) parliamentary candidates]]\n", "name_user": "TrottieTrue", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixed typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rob_Flello"}
